const faqSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: [
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Do immune gummies actually work?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Immune gummies containing clinically studied ingredients at effective doses can support immune function. Vitamin C, zinc, elderberry, and vitamin D each have published randomized controlled trials demonstrating measurable effects on immune markers or illness duration. A 2017 BMJ meta-analysis found that vitamin D supplementation reduced the risk of acute respiratory infections by 12% overall and 70% in severely deficient individuals. Zinc lozenges have been shown to reduce cold duration by 33% when taken within 24 hours of symptom onset. However, no supplement replaces adequate sleep, exercise, and nutrition as the foundation of immune health.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What is the best ingredient for immune support?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Vitamin D is the single most impactful immune supplement for the general population because 42% of Americans are deficient and deficiency directly impairs immune cell function. Zinc is the second priority, as it is required for the development and function of neutrophils, natural killer cells, and T-lymphocytes. Vitamin C supports multiple immune functions including antimicrobial activity and lymphocyte proliferation. Elderberry provides concentrated anthocyanins that have demonstrated antiviral properties in cell culture studies. The most effective immune gummies combine two or more of these ingredients.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Should I take immune gummies year-round or only during cold season?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Year-round supplementation is more effective than seasonal use because immune function depends on sustained adequate nutrient levels. Vitamin D levels take 8-12 weeks to fully replete from deficient status, and zinc stores also build gradually. Starting supplementation only when you feel sick provides some benefit for zinc and vitamin C, but misses the preventive window for vitamin D and elderberry. For optimal immune protection, take a multi-ingredient immune gummy daily throughout the year and consider increasing vitamin C and zinc intake during peak cold and flu season.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Can I take elderberry, vitamin C, and zinc together?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Yes, these three ingredients work through different immune pathways and can be safely combined. Elderberry provides anthocyanin antioxidants and has demonstrated antiviral properties. Vitamin C supports neutrophil function and acts as an antioxidant to protect immune cells from oxidative damage. Zinc is required for immune cell development and function. Many of the best immune gummies combine all three in a single formula. The only caution is to avoid exceeding the Tolerable Upper Intake Level for zinc (40mg/day) or vitamin C (2000mg/day) when combining multiple supplements.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'How much vitamin C do I need for immune support?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'The RDA for vitamin C is 75mg for women and 90mg for men. For immune support, research suggests that 200mg daily is the optimal dose because this achieves near-saturation of plasma and immune cell vitamin C levels. Doses above 200mg produce minimal additional increases in blood levels because absorption efficiency decreases and renal excretion increases. During active illness, some practitioners recommend 500-1000mg daily for the short-term, as immune cells consume vitamin C rapidly during infection. Mega-doses above 2000mg daily can cause GI distress and kidney stone risk.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Is elderberry safe to take every day?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Elderberry supplements made from properly processed Sambucus nigra extract are safe for daily use. Raw elderberries contain cyanogenic glycosides that can cause nausea and vomiting, but commercial extracts are heat-processed to eliminate these compounds. There is a theoretical concern that elderberry may stimulate cytokine production in autoimmune conditions, but this has not been demonstrated in clinical studies at standard supplementation doses. Consult your healthcare provider before taking elderberry if you have an autoimmune condition or take immunosuppressive medications.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Do immune gummies help prevent COVID?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'No supplement has been proven to prevent COVID-19 infection. However, adequate vitamin D status has been associated with reduced COVID severity in multiple observational studies, and zinc plays a critical role in antiviral immune responses. A 2020 meta-analysis found that vitamin D deficiency was associated with a 3.7-fold increased risk of severe COVID outcomes. Immune gummies should be viewed as part of overall health maintenance — supporting the immune system to function optimally — rather than as specific protection against any single pathogen.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What is the difference between elderberry and echinacea for immunity?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Elderberry (Sambucus nigra) provides concentrated anthocyanins with demonstrated antiviral properties in laboratory studies and a 2019 meta-analysis showing reduced duration and severity of upper respiratory infections. Echinacea (E. purpurea or E. angustifolia) stimulates innate immune cell activity, particularly macrophage and natural killer cell function. A 2014 Cochrane review found limited evidence that echinacea products reduce cold duration. Elderberry has stronger and more consistent clinical evidence for respiratory infection support, while echinacea evidence is mixed and product-dependent.' },
    },
  ],
};
