      <p class="key-stat-txt">of American adults are <strong>vitamin D deficient</strong> (below 20 ng/mL), and an additional 12% are deficient in zinc. Both nutrients are essential for immune cell activation and function. Correcting these deficiencies is the single most impactful step most people can take to support their immune system.</p>
    </div>

    <p>The immune supplement market is flooded with products making bold claims about "boosting" immunity, but the clinical reality is more nuanced. You cannot "boost" a healthy immune system beyond its optimal function — and an overactive immune system is what causes autoimmune diseases and cytokine storms. What supplements can do is provide the raw materials your immune system needs to function at its designed capacity, filling the nutritional gaps that decades of processed food diets and indoor lifestyles have created.</p>

